modules.name: Node.Globals
modules.comments:
Global objects exposed by Node.js. See also the [Node.js API
documentation](https://nodejs.org/api/globals.html).

declarations.comments:
The name of the directory that the currently executing script resides in.

Note that this will probably not give you a very useful answer unless you
have bundled up your PureScript code using `psc-bundle`!
declarations.title: __dirname

declarations.comments:
The absolute path of the code file being executed.

Note that this will probably not give you a very useful answer unless you
have bundled up your PureScript code using `psc-bundle`!
declarations.title: __filename

declarations.comments:
Just calls `require`. You might also consider using the FFI instead. This
function is, in general, horribly unsafe, and may perform side effects.
declarations.title: unsafeRequire

declarations.comments:
`require.resolve()`. Use the internal `require` machinery to look up the
location of a module, but rather than loading the module, just return the
resolved filename.
declarations.title: requireResolve

modules.name: Node.Platform
modules.comments:
This module defines data type for the different platforms supported by
Node.js

declarations.comments: The String representation for a platform, recognised by Node.js.
declarations.title: toString

modules.name: Node.Process
modules.comments: Bindings to the global `process` object in Node.js. See also [the Node API documentation](https://nodejs.org/api/process.html)

declarations.comments: An effect tracking interaction with the global `process` object.
declarations.title: PROCESS

declarations.comments:
Register a callback to be performed when the event loop empties, and
Node.js is about to exit. Asynchronous calls can be made in the callback,
and if any are made, it will cause the process to continue a little longer.
declarations.title: onBeforeExit

declarations.comments:
Register a callback to be performed when the process is about to exit.
Any work scheduled via asynchronous calls made here will not be performed
in time.

The argument to the callback is the exit code which the process is about
to exit with.
declarations.title: onExit

declarations.comments: Install a handler for a particular signal.
declarations.title: onSignal

declarations.comments:
Get an array containing the command line arguments. Be aware
that this can change over the course of the program.
declarations.title: argv

declarations.comments:
Node-specific options passed to the `node` executable. Be aware that
this can change over the course of the program.
declarations.title: execArgv

declarations.comments:
The absolute pathname of the `node` executable that started the
process.
declarations.title: execPath

declarations.comments:
Change the current working directory of the process. If the current
directory could not be changed, an exception will be thrown.
declarations.title: chdir

declarations.comments: Get the current working directory of the process.
declarations.title: cwd

declarations.comments: Get a copy of the current environment.
declarations.title: getEnv

declarations.comments: Lookup a particular environment variable.
declarations.title: lookupEnv

declarations.comments: Set an environment variable.
declarations.title: setEnv

declarations.comments:
Cause the process to exit with the supplied integer code. An exit code
of 0 is normally considered successful, and anything else is considered a
failure.
declarations.title: exit

declarations.comments:
The standard input stream. Note that this stream will never emit an `end`
event, so any handlers attached via `onEnd` will never be called.
declarations.title: stdin

declarations.comments:
The standard output stream. Note that this stream cannot be closed; calling
`end` will result in an exception being thrown.
declarations.title: stdout

declarations.comments:
The standard error stream. Note that this stream cannot be closed; calling
`end` will result in an exception being thrown.
declarations.title: stderr

declarations.comments:
Check whether the standard output stream appears to be attached to a TTY.
It is a good idea to check this before printing ANSI codes to stdout
(e.g. for coloured text in the terminal).
declarations.title: stdoutIsTTY

declarations.comments:
Check whether the standard error stream appears to be attached to a TTY.
It is a good idea to check this before printing ANSI codes to stderr
(e.g. for coloured text in the terminal).
declarations.title: stderrIsTTY

declarations.comments: Get the Node.js version.
declarations.title: version
